- w3schools: [querySelector](https://www.w3schools.com/jsref/met_document_queryselector.asp)
- you can use any CSS: [example](https://github.com/edwardtanguay/livecoding-2022-03-28-tasks/blob/master/spa/js/main.js)
	-------------------------------
	const navHomeElem = document.querySelector('nav ul li:nth-child(1)');
	navHomeElem.addEventListener('click', () => {
		hideAllPages();
		pageHomeElem.style.display = 'block';
	});
	-------------------------------

- the focus event occurs when an element gets focus, e.g. a texbox
	---------------------------------------------	
	<input class="info" type="text"	/>

	const infoElem = document.querySelector('.info'); 
	infoElem.addEventListener('focus', () => {
		messageElem.style.backgroundColor = 'yellow';
	});
	---------------------------------------------
- w3schools: [focus](https://www.w3schools.com/jsref/event_onfocus.asp)

- enables you to attach an event to an element
- this element can be a button or any other element, e.g. DIV
- if you attach an event to a non-button element, you may want to add a `cursor: pointer` style to it give the user a visual cue that it is clickable
- example
	-------------------------------------------
	btnEditElem.addEventListener('click', () => {
		const firstNameElem = btnEditElem.parentElement.parentElement.children[0];
		const lastNameElem = btnEditElem.parentElement.parentElement.children[1];
		firstNameElem.innerHTML = `<input value="${firstNameElem.innerText}"/>`;
		lastNameElem.innerHTML = `<input value="${lastNameElem.innerText}"/>`;
	});
	-------------------------------------------
- w3schools: [addEventListener](https://www.w3schools.com/jsref/met_element_addeventlistener.asp)
